ce:section.ce:para:
Three kinds of CDs from different carbon source and synthetic methods were prepared according to literatures. The difference in surficial elemental composition, structural characters and fluorescence property can be analyzed through XPS, UV–vis absorption spectra and PL spectra tests, respectively. The XPS spectra and high-solution C 1s and N 1s spectra were presented in Fig. 1
                        . Compared with the elemental composition of carbon source (Table 1
                        ), the surface of CDs presented a higher C/H ration (C: carbon atom; H: hetero atom, including N atom and O atom). It is generally accepted that there are four stages in the forming process of CDs, including polymerization, aromatization, nucleation, and growth [30,31]. Hetero-atom-included amino-groups and carboxyl-groups play an important role in the pre-polymerizing and aromatizing process through dehydration and crosslinking reactions among carbon source molecules. Hence, there remains some hetero atoms on the surface of CDs. From the high-resolution XPS N 1s spectra of CDs, the N 1s band could be separated into three major peaks at about 398, 399 and 400 eV, representing pyridinic N, amino N, and pyrrolic N [32–35].
